gical, and institutional underpinnings can transcend denominational divides, and that strategies for social change often associated with secular feminism have ties to spiritually inspired social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChurch and social problemsxHistoryy20th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aYWCA.  acatholic.  acivil rights.  aprotestant.  asocial change.  asocial progress.  atraditional family.  awomen's history.  ayoung women's christian association.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813588506?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813588506423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813588506/original  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK